Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

          Findings and Recommendations
          ----------------------------

Finding 1: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is 8.78 active sessions, 53.69% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations
were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 8.77 active sessions, 53.69% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 38 K and the
      average time per write was 2 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 24 M per second for reads
      and 45 M per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and
      recovery, 64% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 35% by
      all other activity.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 8.77 active sessions, 53.69% of total activity.

      I/O and Cluster wait for TABLE PARTITION "TDS.MAIL_PIECE.SYS_P70379"
      with object ID 510176 consumed 82% of the database time spent on this
      SQL statement.


Finding 3: "User I/O" wait Class
Impact is 2.75 active sessions, 16.83% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
The throughput of the I/O subsystem was not significantly lower than expected.

   No recommendations are available.


Finding 4: Top Segments by "User I/O" and "Cluster"
Impact is 1.73 active sessions, 10.56% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Individual database segments responsible for significant "User I/O" and
"Cluster" waits were found.

   Recommendation 1: Segment Tuning
   Estimated benefit is .78 active sessions, 4.77% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic involving I/O on INDEX "TDS.EVENT_PK" with
      object ID 96401.
      Related Object
         Database object with ID 96401.
   Action
      Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming
      significant I/O on this segment. For example, the INSERT statement with
      SQL_ID "7wcmwtk6ay1c9" is responsible for 100% of "User I/O" and
      "Cluster" waits for this segment.
   Rationale
      The I/O usage statistics for the object are: 0 full object scans, 789505
      physical reads, 787410 physical writes and 0 direct reads.

   Recommendation 2: Segment Tuning
   Estimated benefit is .6 active sessions, 3.64% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic involving I/O on INDEX
      "TDS.IDX_PA_ITEM_GUID" with object ID 534450.
      Related Object
         Database object with ID 534450.
   Action
      Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming
      significant I/O on this segment. For example, the ALTER INDEX statement
      with SQL_ID "3xnxn96ta8wdv" is responsible for 100% of "User I/O" and
      "Cluster" waits for this segment.
   Rationale
      The I/O usage statistics for the object are: 0 full object scans,
      1114918 physical reads, 544699 physical writes and 0 direct reads.

   Recommendation 3: Segment Tuning
   Estimated benefit is .35 active sessions, 2.15% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------

      "TDS.MAIL_PIECE.SYS_P70379" with object ID 510176.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:

Finding 5: Soft Parse
Impact is .5 active sessions, 3.09% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------
Soft parsing of SQL statements was consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .5 active sessions, 3.09% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic to keep open the frequently used cursors.
      Note that cursors are closed by both cursor close calls and session
      disconnects.

   Recommendation 2: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .5 active sessions, 3.09% of total activity.
   -----------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider increasing the session cursor cache size by increasing the
      value of parameter "session_cached_cursors".
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "session_cached_cursors" was "50" during the
      analysis period.


Finding 6: Shared Pool Latches
Impact is .38 active sessions, 2.35% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Contention for latches related to the shared pool was consuming significant
database time.
Waits for "library cache: mutex X" amounted to 1% of database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .38 active sessions, 2.35% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for latch contention using the given blocking
      sessions or modules.
   Rationale
      The session with ID 854 and serial number 11770 in instance number 1 was
      the blocking session responsible for 19% of this recommendation's
      benefit.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Concurrency" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .46 active sessions, 2.82% of total activity.
